gee experience and the various relief strategies developed by the major Jewish centers of the day.Teller pays particular attention to those thousands of Jews sent for sale on the slave markets of Istanbul and the extensive transregional Jewish economic network that coalesced to ransom them. He also explores how Jewish communities rallied to support the refugees in central and western Europe, as well as in Poland-Lithuania, doing everything possible to help them overcome their traumatic experiences and rebuild their lives.“Rescue the Surviving Souls” offers an intimate study of an international refugee crisis, from outbreak to resolution, that is profoundly relevant today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aChmelnyzkyj-Aufstand. 0aFlucht. 0aGewalt. 0aJewish refugees-Poland. 0aJuden. 0aOsteuropa. 0aVertreibung. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAmsterdam.  aDavid Carcassoni.  aGerman Jews.  aHoly Roman Empire.  aItalian Jewry.  aItalian Jews.  aJewish history.  aKhmelnytsky uprising of 1648.  aNicholas Terpstra.  aPolish Jews.  aRefugees or Migrants.  aReligious Refugees in the Early Modern World.  aRobert Chazan.  aRussian Muscovite invasion.  aSabbatheanism.  aSephardi philanthropic network.  aSwedish incursion.  adisplacement trauma.  aearly modern history.  aexile.  aforced migrants.  aforced migration.  agezeirot tah ve-tat.  aglobal Jewish network.  ahuman trafficking in Mediterraean.  amajor Jewish communities.  arefugee studies.  areligious history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 E